Oklahoma purchase credit card transactions project¶

The Office of Management and Enterprise Services in the State of Oklahoma has made its purchase credit card transactions available. This dataset contains information on purchases made through the purchase card programs administered by the state and higher education institutions.

# Converting Transaction_Date and Posted_date from Python Object data type to datetime
df['Transaction_Date']=pd.to_datetime(df['Transaction_Date'])
df['Posted_Date']=pd.to_datetime(df['Posted_Date'])

df['Year_Month'].dtype
df['Year_Month']=pd.to_datetime(df['Year_Month'], format='%Y%m')
df['Year'] = df['Year_Month'].dt.year
df['Month'] = df['Year_Month'].dt.month
#Creating 'Week_Number' from 'Transaction_Date'
df['Week_Number'] = df['Transaction_Date'].dt.isocalendar().week

#Creating 'Day_of_Week' from 'Transaction_Date'
dayOfWeek={0:'Monday', 1:'Tuesday', 2:'Wednesday', 3:'Thursday', 4:'Friday', 5:'Saturday', 6:'Sunday'}
df['Day_of_Week'] = df['Transaction_Date'].dt.dayofweek.map(dayOfWeek)

Feature Engineering-----Merchant Part ¶

Instructions:¶

  • Understand the data grain: each row is a cardholder (last name + first name)
  • An agency can have multiple cardholders. A corporate card (agency_name) can be used by many cardholders and these cardholders have to follow the corporation policy.
  • Intuition: One or two cardholders may abuse their corporate cards. If we compare a cardholder to his agency, we can find outliers.
  • The spending for a merchant category can be higher than others. It does not make sense to compare the spending of a merchant category to another. An agency can spend on various merchant categories, and you cannot claim anomalies just because the spending on one merchant category is higher than another.
  • Anomaly detection is about "comparing a transaction to a benchmark". What is the right benchmark?
  • So we will aggregate to the Aggrecy_Name level and card holder level then build features.
  • Common sense tells us the comparison should be at "Agency_Name" and "Merchant_Category" level.

2.3 Feature 3: The ratio to average amount by month period ¶

  • The above two feature talkes about the amount of money spending on each agency and merchant catagory without time limitaion.
  • Insight: people's need on different merchant catagory is different based on different month. For exaxple, during July and August(summer break), the demand for hotel is higher than usual. This kind of transations may be considered as anomalies when compare with the avrage amount of the whole data, but it is reasonable at certain month.
  • It has to be ratio, because differnt merchant catagories has differnt unit prize.
  • It is a combination of feature agency + merchant category + month
  • It is average amount per day over a 30 days period on all transactions up to this one on the same merchant as this transaction

Both feature 1 and feature 3 are cutted by percentail, they both have 7 catagories. But it is intuitive that the thresholds of them are dinstinct when we consider by a month period.

  • feature 1 Text(7, 0, '(8.712, 2.1910012187157464e+16]')]
  • feature 3 : Text(7, 0, '(8.05, 3.0596329968448308e+16]')]

The top 1% transation has 0.7 times differnce in the ratio to average amount of whole transaction or transation within the same month. It is necessary to add the month into consideration.

2.5 Feature 5: The ratio to average amount by day of week¶

  • I Will not consider the ratio to amount by week in this case study. It is not to say that the feature about amount by week is not significant. First, the work step about amount by week is similar to the above average amount by month. Second, compared with average amount by day of week, it will show less information when considering about consumption behavior.
  • Intuition: Some merchant are only consumed in certain day of week. The purchase process of differnt merchant is distinct. People will buy grocery daily, but prefer to deal with the long time purchase in the weekends.
  • Notice the only difference to the above code is "Day_of_Week".

2.7 Feature 7: Merchant popularity: Total transaction ¶

  • This feature is aggregated by number of transaction
  • A lot of merchant catagories only have one transaction history. However, there are some categories
  • More transactions mean this kind of merchant category is more popular. Is the anomalies relative to the popularity of merchant category? Dose unauthorized behavir more likely to happen on these popular merchant or unpopular merchant? This feature can show the popularity of a merchant category.
  • Guess: The fradulence on credit card always happens on the merchant categories we never see daily or some popular category, like grocery and Uber. The transaction amount might be a reflection of merchant popularity.

Data exploration:¶

A lot of merchant categories only have one transaction history. However, there are some categories having a lot of transactions. How to make this transaction data meaningful for this feature engineering?

Feature Engineering-----Cardholder Part ¶

Outlook:¶

  • In this part, I will create feature from primarily the side of cardholder.
  • The comsumption habit and consumption level of a cardholder is hard to change. They also keep a same frequence and amount on their consumption. It makes sense to compare the spending of a cardholder to another. You cannot claim anomalies just because the spending on cardholder is higher than another.
  • So we will aggregate card holder level then build features.
  • Common sense tells us the comparison should be at "Cardholder Last Name" and "Cardholder First Initial" level.

2.10 Feature 10: The ratio to average amount by cardholder name by month¶

  • The above two feature talkes about the amount of money spending on each cardholder without time limitaion.
  • Insight: Every cardholder has different consumption habit. It might be relative to the month. For example, some people would like to consume a lot during the summer break. When we compare the average amount of spending with time period limitation, we can have more precise data to detect anomalies.
  • It has to be ratio, because differnt cardholder has differnt consumption level.
  • It is a combination of cardholder last name + cardholder first name + month
  • It is average amount per day over a 30 days period on all transactions up to this one on the same cardholder as this transaction

  • For Cardholder part, I can do more on amount of spending, aggregating by week, week of day, which I did on merchant part

With the trained model clf, we can apply to the test dataset to predict outliers. The function decision_functions() generates the anomaly score based on your model predictions.

Step 2:Determine a reasonable boundary¶

  • It is impossible to give a clear visual look because the data size is too large
  • There is only one histgram becasue the data not standardized. It is too large to draw the graph.

A data point with a high anomaly score is abnormal. We can use a histogram to find those points. The histogram below shows the count by the anomaly score. Most of the data points have low anomaly scores. If we choose 1.0 to be the cut point, we can suggest those >=1.0 to be outliers. Notice we use the anomaly scores of the training data to determine the boundary.

from pyod.models.combination import aom, moa, average, maximization
from pyod.utils.utility import standardizer
# Standardize data
X_train_norm, X_test_norm = standardizer(X_train, X_test)
# There will be 14 k-NN models.
n_clf = 14
k_list = [20, 30, 40, 50, 70, 80, 90, 110, 
 120, 130, 150, 160, 180, 190]
# Just prepare data frames so we can store the model results
train_scores = np.zeros([X_train.shape[0], n_clf])
test_scores = np.zeros([X_test.shape[0], n_clf])
train_scores.shape
# Modeling
for i in range(n_clf):
    k = k_list[i]
    clf = KNN(n_neighbors=k, method='largest')
    clf.fit(X_train_norm)

    # Store the results in each column:
    train_scores[:, i] = clf.decision_scores_
    test_scores[:, i] = clf.decision_function(X_test_norm) 
# Decision scores have to be normalized before combination
train_scores_norm, test_scores_norm = standardizer(train_scores,test_scores)

Achieve Model Stability by Aggregating Multiple Models¶

The solution is to train multiple models then aggregate the scores. By aggregating multiple models, the chance of overfitting is greatly reduced and the prediction accuracy will be improved.

Conclusion¶

what KNNs is¶

  • The Nearest-neighbor methods are applicable for both unsupervised as well as supervised learning. But for this credit card transactions detection, I use supervised learning because there is no predictive outcome.
  • The unsupervised k-NN method computes the Euclidean distance of an observation to other observations. The unsupervised KNN does not have any parameters to tune to make the performance better. It simply computes the distances to neighbors.

Analysis why I identify above those credit card transactions as anomalous.¶

  • Use KNNs to get the score of each feature for each credit card transaction
  • Draw histgram to show the outliers.
  • Outlier boundary is clear to finger out
  • Not only use one method, but try to analize Average, Maximum of Maximum (MOM), Average of Maximum (AOM) and Maximum of Average (MOA) for score to prevent overfitting and improve accuracy in detection

Business Insight¶

  • Fraud detection systems should be capable of detective work on-line transactions.
  • My graph can gives a visusal explanation to the business people
  • There are about 5% transactions are abnormal, it is reasonable.
